    "---\n",
    "## Section 7: Categorical Encoding (One-Hot Encoding of MARITAL)\n",
    "\n",
    "`MARITAL` has six unordered categories:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Code | Meaning |\n",
    "|---|---|\n",
    "| 1 | Married |\n",
    "| 2 | Divorced |\n",
    "| 3 | Widowed |\n",
    "| 4 | Separated |\n",
    "| 5 | Never married |\n",
    "| 6 | Unmarried couple |\n",
    "\n",
    "This variable is **nominal** (the categories have no meaningful numeric order), so it\n",
    "cannot be left as a raw integer. Leaving it as a number would imply that \"Divorced (2)\n",
    "is twice Married (1)\", which is statistically incorrect and would distort the model.\n",
    "\n",
    "One-hot encoding creates a separate binary column for each category. `drop_first=True`\n",
    "removes `MARITAL_1` (Married) to serve as the **reference category**. This means all\n",
    "other marital status coefficients in the model will be interpreted as \"compared to\n",
    "being married.\" This aligns with clinical research, which consistently shows divorced\n",
    "and widowed individuals have higher depression rates relative to married individuals."
   ]
